I suspect that AI is incapable of remembering anything. It seems to regenerate everything anew each time, drawing solely from its base tokens rather than building upon them with complete words, sentences, methods, or blocks of text—precisely the elements it should have retained in memory. Consequently, it appears that every single word, sentence, and method must be regenerated repeatedly from these base tokens. This approach surely cannot be as intelligent as human cognition; it was bound to become apparent sooner or later. Yet, somehow—only just now—has it truly dawned on me why we are dealing with an "Emptiness Machine" in the context of LLMs: they fundamentally lack an ability that we humans possess—a deficiency they have managed to conceal for as long as possible. At the same time, we have puzzled over why we constantly felt the need to feed our superior contextual understanding back into these LLMs, or why high-quality human-generated content was so frequently—and erroneously—flagged as poor or in violation of guidelines by these AIs. Meanwhile, AI-generated spam is becoming increasingly ubiquitous, and people are gradually realizing that their own content is—and should be—the standard for regeneration, simply because anything they produce themselves is superior to what the LLMs have managed to deliver. What are your thoughts on this? Is the concept of the "Emptiness Machine" applicable to LLMs? Do you perceive this problem in the exact same way I do, or do you view it differently? Many thanks! — Let's Play
